values.comments:
French Impressionism is the centerpiece of this course, which will explore paintings, and some sculptures, produced between 1848 and 1906. The class considers French, Dutch, and Scandanavian artists who painted and exhibited in Paris during these years, exploring not only their historical stature and reputation, but their contemporary relevance. It will reflect on such myths of modernism as the "misogyny"of Degas; the "obsessiveness" of Cezanne; the "primitivism" of Gauguin; and, of course, the "madness" of Van Gogh. All art is considered within the context of the social, economic and political changes that were taking place in Paris--the capital of the nineteenth--century.&#8232;&#8232;

Students generally enjoyed the “highly engaging” course. They appreciated that they “discussed so much more than arts in this class.” Other topics, which included prostitution, photography, physiognomy and more, were “fascinating in their own right and even more interesting when connected by the professor to the art of the Impressionists.” The course exposed students to “a variety of themes and methodologies.”&#8232;&#8232;

Students commented that Professor Dombrowski’s way of teaching was both “smart and fascinating.” Students appreciated that he asked “questions that were tough, well-considered, and provocative, while creating a learning-friendly and compassionate atmosphere in the classroom.” Professor Dombrowski’s ability to artfully summarize large amounts of complex historical and theoretical intro was “nothing less than astounding.” &#8232;&#8232;

Despite the fascinating course design and the professor, some students complained that too much work was required for this course. Notwithstanding the vast amount of work, which included long readings and many papers, however, students recommended this course to anyone interested in the subject.
